Diagnosis (
Figs 30
, 
105
)

. 

Amblycerus spondiae

is characterized by the following characters combination: eyes distant from each other anteriorly, ocular index: 2.7 (
Fig. 30
); pronotum subquadrate with lateral margins slightly curved and lateral carina almost reaching the posterior margin of pronotum (
Figs 54, 56
), with median strip of setae and tufts in lateral margins (
Fig. 56
); scutellum tridentate with median tooth longer than the lateral ones (Fig. 73); first tarsomere about 3.5 times the length of the median spur; median lobe of male genitalia about 4.4 times as long as its greatest width at apical region (
Fig. 105
); internal sac in the apical region with a pair of hollow, subtriangular sclerites (
Fig. 105
). It shares some similarities externally and in relation to genitalia with 

A. alternatus

, but differs from it by the distinct frontoclypeal suture (indistinct in 

A. alternatus

), cervical boss with three setae (two setae in 

A. alternatus

); metaventrite with median sulcus longer than a half the lenght of metaventrite (about half as long as metaventrite in 

A. alternatus

) and apical region with a pair of hollow, subtriangular, non-tuberculate sclerites (with a pair of hollow, subtriangular tuberculate sclerites in 

A. alternatus

). 

Amblycerus spondiae

differs from 

A. cuernavacensis

by the lateral carina almost reaching the posterior margin of pronotum (reaching the posterior margin of pronotum in 

A. cuernavacensis

), cervical boss with three setae (two setae in 

A. cuernavacensis

) and scutellum tridentate with median tooth longer than the others (all teeth with same length in 

A. cuernavacensis

). 

Amblycerus spondiae

differs from 

A. vitis

by the apical sclerite with acute, curved apex (apical sclerite with acute, straight apex in 

A. vitis

) and in median region with a short, unpaired wishbone sclerite (longer wishbone sclerite in 

A. vitis

).
